What is WINRM listner ?

It is a management service that implements a WS-management protocol to send and
receive messages.

WinRM is a listener service.

A listener is defined by a transport (HTTP/HTTPS) and an IPv4 or IPv6 address.

You can create more than one WinRM listener instance on a single computer by giving
them a different TCP-IP address or port number.

Authentication for WinRM Remote Connections

WinRM maintains security for communication between computers by supporting several
standard methods of authentication and message encryption.

Default group access: During setup, WinRM creates a local group (Remote
Management Users). WinRM then restricts remote access to any users who are not a
member of either the local administrators group or the remote management users group.
You can add local/domain users or domain groups to the Remote Management Users
group.

(Types of Security Standards used by WinRM)

Kerberos: It is the default method of authentication when the client is in a domain.
Negotiate: It is the default method of authentication when the client is not in a domain.

If you specify Negotiate, Digest, or Basic authentication and fail to supply a
connection option object, then you will receive an error indicating that explicit
credentials are required.

If HTTPS is not the transport, then the target remote computer must be
configured in the list of TrustedHost computer.

Basic Authentication: It is disabled in the default configuration setting for both WinRM
Client and WinRM Server.
UAC Affects access to the WinRM Service: When Negotiate or authentication is used
in a workgroup, only the built-in administrator account can access the service.

To allow all accounts in the administrators group to access this service (WinRM),
set the following registry value:
HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\System

LocalAccountTokenFilterPolicy = 1
IP address cannot be used when Kerberos method is used for authentication.

Client certificate:

You must first enable the use of client certificate authentication on both the client
and the service by using the winrm.cmd tool.

You must also create an entry in the cert mapping table on the WinRM Server
computer. This establishes a mapping between one or more certificates and a
local account.

Once the certificate is used for authentication and authorization, the
corresponding local account is used for operations performed by the WinRM
Service.

Maximum size of certificate usable by WinRM is 16KB.


